# Data Modelling – Topic 7: Snowflake Schema

# First — Recall Star Schema

In a **Star Schema**:

* fact table at center
* dimensions around it
* dimensions are usually denormalized

Example:
## dim_product
| product_key | product_name | category | brand |
| ----------- | ------------ | -------- | ----- |
Everything inside one dimension table.
Simple and fast.
---
# What is Snowflake Schema?
## Theory
A **Snowflake Schema** is a dimensional model where dimension tables are further normalized into multiple related tables.
Meaning:
Instead of one large dimension table, dimensions are split into smaller tables.
---

# Example — Product Dimension
## Star Schema Version
### dim_product
| product_key | product_name | category | brand |
| ----------- | ------------ | -------- | ----- |
Single dimension table.
---
## Snowflake Version
### dim_product
| product_key | product_name | category_key | brand_key |
### dim_category
| category_key | category_name |
### dim_brand
| brand_key | brand_name |
Now dimensions themselves are normalized.
---
Star schema:
* simple star shape
Snowflake:
* branching normalized structure
---

# Core Difference from Star Schema

| Feature     | Star Schema  | Snowflake Schema |
| ----------- | ------------ | ---------------- |
| Dimensions  | Denormalized | Normalized       |
| Joins       | Fewer        | More             |
| Query Speed | Faster       | Slightly slower  |
| Redundancy  | More         | Less             |
| Complexity  | Simple       | More complex     |
| Storage     | More         | Less             |

---

# Why Snowflake Schema Exists
Normalization inside dimensions helps:
* reduce redundancy
* improve consistency
* save storage
* centralize hierarchy management
---

# Example — Real Retail Hierarchy
Suppose thousands of products belong to categories.
If category repeated in every product row:

| product | category    |
| ------- | ----------- |
| iPhone  | Electronics |
| TV      | Electronics |
| Laptop  | Electronics |
“Electronics” repeated everywhere.
Snowflake schema separates category table.
---

# Real Warehouse Example
At Amazon:
## Fact Table
fact_sales
---
## Snowflaked Product Dimension
dim_product
   |
dim_subcategory
   |
dim_category
```
Product hierarchy normalized.
---
# Advantages of Snowflake Schema ⭐
## 1. Reduced Redundancy
Less duplicate data.
---
## 2. Better Data Integrity
Category updates happen in one place.
---
## 3. Smaller Storage
Useful for huge dimensions.
---
## 4. Better Hierarchy Management
Complex organizational structures easier.
---
# Disadvantages ⚠️
## 1. More Joins
Analytics queries become more complex.
---
## 2. Slower Queries
Compared to star schema.
---
## 3. Harder for BI Users
Business teams prefer simpler star schema.
---
# Important Interview Insight ⭐
Most modern warehouses prefer:
✅ Star Schema for performance & simplicity
Snowflake used selectively when:
* dimensions huge
* hierarchies complex
* redundancy problematic
This is the practical answer.
---

# Example Query Comparison
## Star Schema Query
SELECT category, SUM(revenue)
FROM fact_sales f
JOIN dim_product p
ON f.product_key = p.product_key
GROUP BY category;
```
Simple.
---
## Snowflake Query
SELECT c.category_name, SUM(f.revenue)
FROM fact_sales f
JOIN dim_product p
ON f.product_key = p.product_key
JOIN dim_category c
ON p.category_key = c.category_key
GROUP BY c.category_name;
```
Extra joins.
---
# Star vs Snowflake — Real Thinking
## Star Schema Optimizes
* performance
* simplicity
* BI usability
---

## Snowflake Optimizes
* storage
* normalization
* hierarchy consistency
---

# Common Interview Questions
## Q1. Difference between Star and Snowflake?
Star uses denormalized dimensions.
Snowflake normalizes dimensions into multiple related tables.
---

## Q2. Which performs better?
Usually Star Schema.
---

## Q3. Why use Snowflake then?
Better storage efficiency and hierarchy management.
---
## Q4. Which is more normalized?
Snowflake schema.
